items.title: Lyft to buy taxi app FREENOW for $197M to enter Europe
items.author: Rebecca Bellan
items.summary:
- Lyft agrees to acquire FREENOW for approximately $197 million in cash.
- This acquisition marks Lyft's entry into the European market, where it has not operated before.
- FREENOW operates in nine countries and over 150 cities across Europe.
- The deal is anticipated to close in the second half of 2025.
- FREENOW has reported year-on-year growth of 13% and recently reached break-even.
- The merger is expected to nearly double Lyft's total addressable market and increase annualized gross bookings by about $1.14 billion.
- There will be no immediate changes to FREENOW's customer experience; integration plans are underway.

items.title: AMD estimates $800M charge on US license requirement for AI chips
items.author: Kyle Wiggers
items.summary:
• AMD announced potential $800 million charge due to U.S. export license requirements for AI chips to certain countries, including China.
• The license specifically affects AMD's MI308 GPUs, with uncertainty about obtaining the necessary licenses.
• AMD's stock dropped approximately 7% in pre-market trading following the announcement.
• Rivals like Nvidia are also affected, expecting $5.5 billion in related charges.
• U.S. officials emphasize that these export controls aim to protect national security and the U.S.'s AI dominance.

items.title: Patreon tests a native live video feature where creators can stream 24/7
A dev built a test to see how AI chatbots respond to controversial topics
items.author: Kyle Wiggers
items.summary:
- A developer created a tool called [SpeechMap](https://speechmap.ai/) to evaluate how different AI chatbots respond to controversial topics.
- The tool compares responses from models like [ChatGPT](https://techcrunch.com/2025/04/11/chatgpt-everything-to-know-about-the-ai-chatbot/#:~:text=ChatGPT%2C%20OpenAI's%20text%2Dgenerating%20AI) and [Grok](https://techcrunch.com/2024/03/29/what-is-elon-musks-grok-chatbot-and-how-does-it-work/) on sensitive subjects.
- The developer's goal was to stimulate public discourse about AI model limitations.
- Trends revealed that OpenAI's models are becoming less responsive to political questions, while Grok 3 shows a high compliance rate of 96.2%.
- The article also discusses allegations of AI chatbots being overly “woke” and the response of AI companies to adjust their models accordingly.

items.title: X’s UK division saw revenue decline 66% in 2023 following Musk’s takeover
items.summary:
- Revenues for X (formerly Twitter) U.K. division collapsed by over 60% in 2023.
- Revenue dropped 66.3% to £69.1 million ($91.6 million) from £205.3 million ($272.3 million) year-on-year.
- The decline is attributed to reduced advertising spending due to concerns over brand safety and content moderation.
- Profit fell to £1.2 million ($1.6 million) from £5.6 million ($7.4 million) in the same period.
- Employee numbers in the U.K. decreased from 399 to 114 following Musk's takeover and layoffs.

items.title: Cosmic Robotics’ robots could speed up solar panel deployments
items.author: Tim De Chant
items.summary:
- The U.S. faces a shortage of solar panel installers due to increased solar farm construction.
- Cosmic Robotics has developed a robotic assistant to ease the physical burden on workers.
- Cosmic recently raised $4 million in a pre-seed round led by Giant Ventures.
- The robot can install a solar panel every 30 to 40 seconds and helps to double installation efficiency.
- By the end of the year, Cosmic plans to manufacture robots for production environments.

items.title: Hammerspace, an unstructured data wrangler used by Nvidia, Meta and Tesla, raises $100M at $500M+ valuation
items.author: Ingrid Lunden
items.summary:
- Hammerspace has raised $100 million in funding, valuing the company at over $500 million.
- Investors include Altimeter Capital and ARK Invest, among others.
- The company is aimed at helping organizations efficiently access and manage unstructured data for AI applications.
- Major clients include NVIDIA, Meta, Tesla, and the Department of Defense.
- Hammerspace plans to use the funds to enhance sales and marketing efforts, building on its previous growth through word-of-mouth.
- The technology is based on a unique file system using the Linux kernel NFS client, developed by co-founder Trond Myklebust.
- CEO David Flynn has indicated plans for an IPO within approximately two years, dependent on market conditions.

items.title: Google used AI to suspend over 39M ad accounts suspected of fraud
items.author: Jagmeet Singh
items.summary:
- Google suspended 39.2 million advertiser accounts in 2024, a significant increase from the previous year.
- The company utilized large language models (LLMs) and signals like business impersonation to identify fraudulent accounts before ads were served.
- In total, Google removed nearly half a billion ads related to scams, with 5 million accounts suspended for scam-related violations.

items.title: Visa-backed African unicorn Moniepoint tackles remittances. But is it late to the game?
items.summary:
- Visa invested in Nigerian fintech Moniepoint, validating its status as a unicorn and signaling a new direction for the company.
- Moniepoint launched MonieWorld to facilitate remittances and cross-border services starting with the UK–Nigeria corridor.
- The remittance market is highly competitive, and Moniepoint will need to differentiate itself from established services that dominate user preferences.

items.title: Opera adds its Aria AI assistant to Opera Mini browser
items.author: Ivan Mehta
items.summary:
- Opera has introduced its AI assistant, Aria, to the Opera Mini browser on Android to assist users with low-end devices and data constraints.
- Aria can provide news updates, answer queries, and generate images using models from OpenAI and Google.
- Opera Mini, launched in 2005, claims to help users save on data while browsing; it has over a billion downloads and more than 100 million global users.
- The company has partnered with local telcos in Africa to provide free data offers to Opera Mini customers, although it faced challenges with regulatory changes in Kenya.
- Opera has ambitious plans for AI, including features for natural language control of tabs and autonomous task completion.

items.title: TS Anil, CEO of Monzo, is joining our StrictlyVC London lineup
items.author: null
items.summary:
- TS Anil, CEO of Monzo, will speak at the StrictlyVC event in London on [May 13](https://techcrunch.com/events/strictlyvc-london-2025/?utm_medium=post&utm_campaign=svclondon&utm_content=ticketsales&utm_source=tc&utm_promo=post_tsanilspeaker_04162025&utm_display=).
- Monzo Bank is known for reshaping the UK’s financial landscape with its digital banking services.
- The event features other notable speakers like Sonali De Rycker from Accel and Nazo Moosa from Paladin Capital Group, focusing on real dialogue with the audience.

items.title: How Musk manages his growing family: WSJ
items.summary:
- Elon Musk claims it’s his duty to "make new humans" and may have fathered more than 14 children, with sources suggesting the real number is higher.
- Jared Birchall, Musk’s longtime fixer, manages logistics related to Musk’s family, including NDAs for mothers of his children.
- A deal proposed to influencer Ashley St. Clair after the birth of their son involved $15 million and $100,000 monthly until the child turned 21, which she refused.

items.title: Grok gains a canvas-like tool for creating docs and apps
Nvidia H20 chip exports hit with license requirement by US government
items.author: Becca Szkutak
items.summary:
- Nvidia must obtain a license to export its H20 AI chips to China due to new US export controls.
- The license requirement is indefinite, prompted by concerns that the chips could be used in Chinese supercomputers.
- Nvidia anticipates $5.5 billion in charges for Q1 2026 following the announcement.
- Nvidia's stock fell approximately 6% in after-hours trading.
- The H20 chip is the most advanced AI chip Nvidia can currently export to China under existing rules.
- Prior to this, CEO Jensen Huang reportedly negotiated with President Trump to avoid new restrictions.
- Nvidia also plans to invest hundreds of millions in AI chip manufacturing in the US over the next four years.

items.title: Figma ignores the fear, files paperwork for an IPO
items.summary:
- Figma has filed confidential paperwork for an IPO as of April 15, 2025.
- The stock market is uncertain due to recent trade policies, making the IPO filing unexpected.
- Previous planned IPOs by Klarna and StubHub were delayed after market crashes.
- Figma was last valued at $12.5 billion in May 2024 after a tender offer for shareholders.
- Adobe's attempt to buy Figma for $20 billion fell through due to regulatory issues.

items.title: Telli, a YC alum, raises pre-seed funding for its AI voice agents
items.author: Seb Hapte-Selassie, Philipp Baumanns, Finn zur Mühlen
items.summary:
- Berlin-based startup Telli raised $3.6 million in pre-seed funding, led by Cherry Ventures and Y Combinator.
- Telli's AI voice agents automate customer operations like appointment bookings, with complex tasks handled by humans.
- The startup claims over 50% month-over-month revenue growth, processing close to a million calls with a six-person team across multiple countries.
- Founders drew inspiration from their experience in scaling customer service at German unicorn Enpal.
- The AI agents utilize voice actors' cloned voices and models from OpenAI, Claude, among others for best performance.

items.title: For security, Android phones will now auto-reboot after three days
items.author: Lorenzo Franceschi-Bicchierai
items.summary:
- Google’s Android will automatically reboot if locked for three consecutive days.
- A security feature added to Google Play services aims to protect data from unauthorized access.
- Similar feature was previously rolled out by Apple for iOS.
- The reboot serves to complicate data extraction by law enforcement using forensic tools.

items.title: TikTok takes on Google Maps by surfacing reviews in the comments tab
items.author: Aisha Malik
items.summary:
- TikTok introduces a new feature that displays user reviews for places in the comments tab of videos.
- Users can see ratings, written reviews, and photos for tagged locations like Central Park when viewing related videos.
- This feature aims to enhance TikTok’s search capabilities and compete with Google Maps.
- TikTok has been expanding its search functionalities, particularly among younger users, as suggested by a Google executive in 2022.
- The feature is currently in testing, and it is uncertain when it will be widely available.

items.title: Stop doomscrolling and watch the ‘Great Moose Migration’ livestream
items.author: Amanda Silberling
items.summary:
- The Great Moose Migration livestream airs for three weeks each spring, allowing global viewers to watch moose cross the Ångerman River.
- The livestream features tranquil scenes from over 30 cameras and had 9 million viewers last year, comparable to popular events like Shark Week.
- Unlike fast-paced online content, this slow-paced nature livestream offers a unique, relaxed viewing experience.

items.title: OpenAI may ‘adjust’ its safeguards if rivals release ‘high-risk’ AI
items.author: Kyle Wiggers
items.summary:
- OpenAI may change its safety requirements if rival AI labs release high-risk systems without adequate safeguards.
- The update follows claims of OpenAI lowering safety standards for rapid model releases, facing scrutiny from former employees.
- New adjustments will only be made after confirming changes in risk landscape, with a promise to maintain safeguards at a protective level.
- OpenAI is increasingly relying on automated evaluations to accelerate product development despite ongoing human-led testing.
- The framework also revises how models are categorized based on their risk, focusing on 'high' and 'critical' capabilities.
- These updates mark the first changes to OpenAI’s Preparedness Framework since 2023.

items.title: India’s BluSmart swept up in Gensol investigation alleging misuse of EV loans
Figma sent a cease-and-desist letter to Lovable over the term ‘Dev Mode’
items.summary:
- Figma has issued a cease-and-desist letter to Lovable regarding the use of the term "Dev Mode" for a new product feature.
- Figma trademarked "Dev Mode" last year, while the term is commonly used across software products including those by Apple, Google, and Microsoft.
- The legal action arises from Figma's desire to protect its trademark, as failing to act could lead to the term becoming generic.
- Some experts argue that the term should never have been trademarked, suggesting Lovable fight back, although it may be costly for the startup.
- Lovable is emerging in the "vibe coding" space, enabling users to create applications through descriptive prompts, which places it in competition with Figma, valued at $12.5 billion a year prior.

items.title: OpenAI hires team behind GV-backed AI eval platform Context.ai
items.author: Ivan Mehta
items.summary:
- Context.ai, a startup focused on AI evaluations, is being acquired by OpenAI.
- The co-founders, Henry Scott-Green and Alex Gamble, will join OpenAI, while Context.ai plans to wind down its products.
- Founded in 2023, Context.ai raised $3.5 million in seed funding from GV and Theory Ventures.
- Context.ai created a dashboard for analyzing AI model data and addressing model performance issues.
- Scott-Green mentioned the need for tools to help developers understand their models better now that they are joining OpenAI.

items.title: Google bets on geothermal to power data centers in Taiwan
items.summary:
- Google will add 10 megawatts of geothermal power in Taiwan, marking its first geothermal investment in Asia.
- The project is being developed by Swedish company Baseload Capital, which has been mapping geothermal resources in Taiwan since 2019.
- This investment follows a previous agreement with geothermal startup Fervo for a 3.5-megawatt power plant in Nevada.
- Geothermal energy could provide up to 90 gigawatts of clean power in the U.S. by 2050, with Taiwan aiming for 6 gigawatts by the same year.

items.title: Anthropic forms a new team to grow its AWS business
Publishing platform Medium says it’s sticking with DEI
items.author: Sarah Perez
items.summary:
- Medium reaffirms commitment to diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) amidst other tech companies scaling back.
- CEO Tony Stubblebine emphasizes that businesses shouldn't have to choose between profit and inclusion.
- Medium aims to provide a civil platform, opposing harmful content unlike competitor Substack, which has faced backlash for its free speech approach.

items.title: Google’s Veo 2 video generating model comes to Gemini
items.author: Kyle Wiggers
items.summary:
- Google launches Veo 2 video-generating AI model for Gemini Advanced subscribers.
- Veo 2 allows creation of eight-second videos at 720p resolution.
- Generated videos can be shared on platforms like TikTok and YouTube.
- Monthly video creation limits apply; Google Workspace plans are not supported.
- Veo 2 integrates with Whisk for creating videos from images.
- Concerns arise regarding the impact of AI on the creative job industry, with projections of job disruptions by 2026.

items.title: Anthropic’s Claude can now read your Gmail
Notorious image board 4chan hacked and internal data leaked
items.author: Lorenzo Franceschi-Bicchierai, Amanda Silberling
items.summary:
- 4chan was hacked on Tuesday, leading to intermittent website outages.
- The hacker claimed to have accessed 4chan’s systems for over a year, leaking internal data including backend screenshots and moderator information.
- The leak could expose the identities of forum operators linked to alt-right movements and highlight existing vulnerabilities in 4chan’s security.

items.title: Deel’s CEO is now in Dubai, complicating Rippling’s lawsuit
Witness a dynamic dialogue between two visionary CEOs
items.summary:
- Fireside chat features Ali Ghodsi, CEO of Databricks, and Dario Amodei, CEO of Anthropic.
- Discussion on the evolution of domain-specific AI agents.
- Event includes access to three additional sessions expanding on the CEO discussion.
- Virtual event scheduled for April 22 and April 23, 2025, in different time zones.
- Learning outcomes include importance of AI agents and real-life customer examples.

items.title: OpenAI is reportedly developing its own X-like social media platform
OpenAI ships GPT-4.1 without a safety report
Former Tesla supply chain leaders create Atomic, an AI inventory solution
items.author: Michael Rossiter, Neal Suidan
items.summary:
- Atomic is founded by former Tesla supply chain leaders Michael Rossiter and Neal Suidan, aiming to streamline supply chains using AI.
- The company secured a $3 million seed round led by DVx Ventures and Madrona Ventures.
- Their AI technology has helped pilot customers reduce inventory levels significantly while maintaining high in-stock rates.
- Atomic’s software allows for quick simulation of multiple inventory scenarios, alleviating time-consuming planning processes.
- The founders emphasize a flexible data model and precision control for inventory planners.
- They intend to support all businesses dealing with physical goods, reflecting a transformational vision similar to their experience at Tesla.

items.title: Here’s how Pacific Fusion plans to build a fusion power plant
items.author: Tim De Chant
items.summary:
- Pacific Fusion emerged from stealth in October with a $900 million Series A funding round.
- The startup's goal is to build a fusion reactor, aiming for 100 times the gain of the National Ignition Facility (NIF) at a tenth of the cost.
- The first commercial reactor is projected to be about a decade away.
- Pacific Fusion uses a unique method involving 156 impedance-matched Marx generators that produce 2 terawatts of power in 100 nanoseconds.
- The company is several months ahead of schedule with prototypes of their technology.
- Regulatory clarity for fusion has improved with the passage of the Advance Act in July 2024.

items.title: Founder’s Fund’s new $4.6B fund indicates an era of big VC spending
items.summary:
- Peter Thiel’s Founder’s Fund has raised a new $4.6 billion growth fund, up from its last $3.4 billion fund in 2022.
- The fund was oversubscribed with 270 LPs participating, indicating high demand from limited partners.
- This raise suggests a shift in the venture market from bear to bull, contrasting with prior trends of reduced fund sizes in 2023.
- Founders Fund not only focuses on AI startups but also emphasizes investment in defense tech, reflecting its diverse investment strategy.
- Notable portfolio companies include Anduril, SpaceX, Flock Safety, and Biofire.

items.title: Mark Zuckerberg once considered deleting all your Facebook friends
items.author: Sarah Perez
items.summary:
- Mark Zuckerberg proposed deleting all Facebook friends to boost cultural relevance.
- This idea, described as "potentially crazy," emerged during the U.S. government's antitrust trial against Meta.
- Zuckerberg suggested forcing users to rebuild their friend connections to re-engage with Facebook.
- The plan was opposed by other Meta executives and never implemented.
- Facebook has recently focused on connecting friends again, revamping the Friends tab for a more original user experience.

items.title: Final days to apply to speak at TechCrunch All Stage
Notion releases an AI-powered email client for Gmail
items.author: Becca
items.summary:
- Notion launched [Notion Mail](https://www.notion.com/product/mail), an AI-powered email client for Gmail, on Tuesday.
- It integrates with Notion's workflow management, helping organize emails, draft responses, and schedule meetings.
- Notion Mail's AI capabilities are available for free with usage limits or through a paid tier.
- Competes in a crowded market with other AI email solutions like [Superhuman](https://techcrunch.com/2025/02/19/superhuman-introduces-ai-powered-categorization-to-reduce-spammy-emails-in-your-inbox/) and [Fyxer](https://www.fyxer.com/).
- Features emphasize creating customizable inboxes, allowing users to configure settings extensively.
- Includes advanced organization functions, such as auto-labeling emails into topic-specific inboxes.
- Integrates with other Notion products like Notion Calendar for seamless scheduling.
- Future plans include more integrations and app versions, plus support for multiple inboxes.

items.title: Reach 1,000+ AI leaders: Host a Side Event during TechCrunch Sessions: AI
items.summary:
- Hosting a [Side Event](https://techcrunch.com/events/tc-sessions-ai/side-events/?promo=post_sideevents_04152025&utm_campaign=tcsessionsai2025&utm_content=sideevents&utm_medium=post&utm_source=tc) during TechCrunch Sessions: AI provides exposure to 1,200+ attendees.
- Events can be held from June 1 to June 7, 2025, alongside the main event on June 5 at Zellerbach Hall, Berkeley.
- Benefits include listings on various TC Sessions platforms, promotional support, and the opportunity to connect with the AI community.

items.title: Lucid Gravity First Drive: An electric SUV that doesn’t make compromises
items.summary:
- Lucid Gravity is designed to compete with luxury EVs and SUVs like Rivian R1S, Cadillac Escalade IQ, BMW X7, and Audi Q8.
- Starting price is $96,550; offers up to 450 miles EPA-rated range and 0-60 mph in under 3.5 seconds.
- Features rapid charging capability, providing 200 miles in just 11 minutes on DC fast charging.
- Luxurious interior with 120 cubic feet of space; significantly more than competitors.
- Uses a Gen 2 powertrain and innovative charging technology in partnership with Panasonic.
- Aims to offer advanced driver assistance features, including Level 3 automation in future updates.
- Available in various trims, including a more affordable $81,550 Touring model expected later this year.

items.title: Fusion power has a fuel problem; Hexium has a laser-powered solution
items.author: Tim De Chant
items.summary:
- Fusion startups face significant challenges, including creating a sustainable power plant and sourcing fuel.
- Tritium, a key ingredient for fusion, is derived from lithium, which is currently in short supply.
- Hexium, founded by Charlie Jerrott and Jacob Peterson, aims to solve this fuel problem using atomic vapor laser isotope separation (AVLIS) technology.
- The company has raised $8 million in seed funding and plans to build a pilot plant to produce lithium-6, which is necessary for tritium fuel.
- Their process requires low-power lasers tuned to interact specifically with lithium-6, allowing for efficient separation from lithium-7.
- Hexium's modular design strategy allows for scaled production without the need for large facilities.

items.title: Phantom Neuro grabs $19M to help amputees put their phantom limbs to use
Apple details how it plans to improve its AI models by privately analyzing user data
items.author: Ivan Mehta
items.summary:
- Apple is addressing criticism regarding its AI products by analyzing user data privately.
- The company will use a method called "differential privacy" to generate synthetic data for model improvement.
- Synthetic data mimics user data but doesn't include actual user content, allowing for more accurate AI model training.
- Apple aims to enhance its AI capabilities in features like email summaries and various writing tools using this approach.

items.title: Waymo and Uber prepare to launch robotaxi service in Atlanta this summer
items.author: Kirsten Korosec
items.summary:
- Uber invites customers in Atlanta to sign up for a Waymo robotaxi service.
- The robotaxi service is set to launch in Atlanta this summer.
- Uber and Waymo previously announced plans for robotaxi services in Austin and Atlanta in early 2025.
- Uber handles vehicle management while Waymo oversees the autonomous technology and operations.
- Only Uber users can hail the fleet of Jaguar I-PACE vehicles.
- The service will cover 65 square miles of Atlanta initially, with plans for future expansion.
- Customers signing up will receive updates and may gain early access to the service.

items.title: Girls Who Code founder Reshma Saujani spills business tea with Meghan, Duchess of Sussex
items.summary:
- Reshma Saujani, founder of Girls Who Code, discussed her journey on Meghan's podcast, "Confessions of a Female Founder."
- Saujani admitted her lack of coding experience but successfully launched Girls Who Code, training over 670,000 individuals in STEM.
- The podcast aims to inspire social entrepreneurship and share female founders' experiences while navigating business and motherhood.

items.title: Marshmallow, the UK insurance startup for migrants, raises $90M at a $2B+ valuation
items.author: Ingrid Lunden
items.summary:
- U.K. startup [Marshmallow](https://www.marshmallow.com/) raises $90 million to expand its services, valued over $2 billion.
- The startup has insured 1 million drivers, reporting an annual revenue run rate of $500 million, focusing on car insurance for migrants.
- Marshmallow aims to diversify into financial services and additional insurance products, helping migrants integrate into life in the U.K.
- CEO Oliver Kent-Braham highlights the growing migrant population, with 1.2 million arrivals in 2024.
- The funding consists of equity and debt, led by Portage Capital, with participation from BlackRock and others.
- Marshmallow previously raised funding at a $1.25 billion valuation in 2021, having grown from 100,000 insured individuals to a million.
- The startup's strategy aims to be a 'one-stop shop' for insurance and financial products for new arrivals.

items.title: RLWRLD raises $14.8M to build a foundational model for robotics
items.author: Not given
items.summary:
- South Korean startup RLWRLD has raised 21 billion KRW (about $14.8 million) in seed funding.
- The funding round was led by Hashed and involves several strategic investors including LG Electronics and SK Telecom.
- RLWRLD aims to automate manual tasks using a foundational AI model that combines large language models with robotics software.
- The startup plans to fund proof-of-concept projects, secure computing infrastructure, and hire research talent.
- They aim to develop advanced robotic capabilities like five-finger movements, surpassing current competitors.
- The company also explores automating human-centric workflows with demonstrations planned for later this year.

items.title: Debates over AI benchmarking have reached Pokémon
items.author: Kyle Wiggers
items.summary:
- A social media post claimed Google’s Gemini model outperformed Anthropic’s Claude model in the original Pokémon games.
- Gemini reportedly reached Lavender Town during a developer Twitch stream, while Claude was still at Mount Moon.
- Benefits of custom minimaps for AI gameplay influence benchmarking results, raising concerns about fair comparison in AI model evaluations.
- Previous AI scores from Anthropic and Meta highlighted the disparities in performance based on custom implementations for benchmarks.
- Custom benchmarks like Pokémon, while popular, are not reliable indicators of a model’s overall capabilities.

items.title: Lime’s scooter and e-bike batteries will be recycled by Redwood Materials
items.author: Kirsten Korosec
items.summary:
- Lime has partnered with Redwood Materials for battery recycling from its scooters and e-bikes.
- Redwood will recover lithium, cobalt, nickel, and copper for reuse in battery manufacturing.
- The partnership covers Lime’s operations in the US, Germany, and the Netherlands but not all regions.
- This is Lime’s first direct relationship with a North American battery recycler.
- Lime aims to decarbonize its business by 2030 and has reduced emissions by 59.5% since 2019.
- Andrew Savage, VP of Sustainability at Lime, highlighted the collaboration’s role in closing the supply chain loop.
- Redwood has partnerships with other companies, including Lyft, for e-bike battery recycling.
